","1295–1314":"1295–1314","1230–1250":"1230–1250","about 1272":"omkring 1272","1314":"1314","about 1270":"omkring 1270","abt 1250":"omkring 1250","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","about 1274":"omkring 1274","1317":"1317","Ogle, Northumberland, England":"Ogle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Shilvington, Morpeth, Northumberland, England":"Shilvington, Morpeth, Northumberland, England"},"nl":{"abt 1250–":"circa 1250–Overleden","1250–Female":"1250–Overleden","1250–1317":"1250–1317","1270–Female":"1270–Overleden","1272–Male":"1272–Overleden","1274–Male":"1274–Overleden","1295–1314":"1295–1314","1230–1250":"1230–1250","about 1272":"circa 1272","1314":"1314","about 1270":"circa 1270","abt 1250":"circa 1250","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","about 1274":"circa 1274","1317":"1317","Ogle, Northumberland, England":"Ogle, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Shilvington, Morpeth, Northumberland, England":"Shilvington, Morpeth, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"abt 1250–":"about 1250–Deceased","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1250–1317":"1250–1317","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1272–Male":"1272–Deceased","1274–Male":"1274–Deceased","1295–1314":"1295–1314","1230–1250":"1230–1250","about 1272":"about 1272","1314":"1314","about 1270":"about 1270","abt 1250":"about 1250","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","about 1274":"about 1274","1317":"1317","Ogle, Northumberland, England":"Ogle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Shilvington, Morpeth, Northumberland, England":"Shilvington, Morpeth, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Morrel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Morrell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Morrell","meanings":["English (northern): from the medieval personal name <i>Morel</i>, a diminutive of Middle English or Old French <i>More</i>. Compare   Moore  .","Americanized form of French   Morel  . Compare   Morell   3."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Morrel was born about 1250, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Michael Morrel. She married Sir Hugh Gobion IV of Shilvington about 1270, in Ogle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"abt 1250–":"umbes 1250–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1250–1317":"1250–1317","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1295–1314":"1295–1314","1230–1250":"1230–1250","about 1272":"umbes 1272","1314":"1314","about 1270":"umbes 1270","abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","about 1274":"umbes 1274","1317":"1317","Ogle, Northumberland, England":"Ogle, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Shilvington, Morpeth, Northumberland, England"